        .col-lg-8

          p.lead.mt-5
            | When you finally make the decision to seek professional help for an addiction, you're immediately hit with a confusing wall of industry jargon. "Residential," "PHP," "IOP," "Levels of Care." What does it all mean? And more importantly, which one do you actually need?

          hr.my-5

          h2.mt-4
            i.bi.bi-building.text-primary.me-2
            | Inpatient (Residential) Treatment
          p
            | **What it is:** Inpatient or "residential" rehab means you live at the facility 24/7 for the duration of your program—typically 28, 60, or 90 days. It is a highly structured, immersive environment where your entire day revolves around recovery, therapy, and group sessions.
          p
            | **Who it's for:** Residential treatment is recommended for people with severe, long-term addictions, those who have previously relapsed after outpatient programs, or individuals who are living in environments where staying sober is impossible (like living with other people who actively use drugs).
          ul
            li
              strong Pros:
              |  Removes you from triggers, provides 24/7 medical and emotional support, allows you to focus 100% on healing.
            li
              strong Cons:
              |  It is expensive (though Medicaid and insurance often cover it in WA), and it requires taking a leave of absence from work and family responsibilities.
          
          h2.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-door-open.text-primary.me-2
            | Outpatient Treatment (IOP & PHP)
          p
            | Outpatient rehab comes in several "levels" depending on how many hours a week you attend. 
          p
            | **Intensive Outpatient Program (IOP):** This is the most common form of rehab. You attend therapy groups and individual counseling at a clinic for 9 to 15 hours a week (usually 3 hours a day, 3-4 days a week).
          p
            | **Partial Hospitalization Program (PHP):** A step up from IOP. You attend the clinic for 5 to 6 hours a day, 5 days a week, but you still sleep in your own bed at night.
          p
            | **Who it's for:** Outpatient is ideal for people with milder substance use disorders, individuals with a safe and supportive home environment, or as a "step-down" after someone completes a 30-day residential program.
          ul
            li
              strong Pros:
              |  More affordable, allows you to continue working or going to school, lets you practice your new sober coping skills in the "real world" immediately.
            li
              strong Cons:
              |  You are still exposed to daily triggers. If your home life is chaotic or unsafe, outpatient therapy is very difficult to maintain.

          h2.mt-5
            i.bi.bi-clipboard-check.text-primary.me-2
            | What is an "Assessment"?
          p
            | The good news is that you don't have to guess which program you need. When you call a treatment center in Spokane, the very first step is a **Clinical Assessment** (sometimes called a SUD evaluation). A licensed counselor will ask you a series of confidential questions about your use history, medical health, and living situation. Based on a standardized tool called the ASAM criteria, they will officially recommend the level of care you need.

